{"id":14881847,"mediaExerciseId":"371d5bf8-0f36-4d29-8c8b-5a1e3ce96393","exerciseName":"5","chapterName":"23","chapterTitle":"Enterprise Risk Management","groupId":612489,"groupTitle":"Minicase Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":789,"solutions":[{"id":6028920,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"**a.** For this, we will use the formula for the fair value of the loan which is given as:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Fair value of loan}&=\\dfrac{\\text{Monthly payment} \\times \\left(1-\\left(1+\\dfrac{R}{12}\\right)^{-n}\\right)}{R}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nWhere,\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Monthly payment}&=\\$2,577.21\\\\\nR&=0.05\\\\\nn&=300\n\\end{aligned}$$\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":427,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/16/21ca37f6ead61620c1672bfd0bdec0d3/d36ae24313c8ae3fdc0fa4d64a398a91/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":213,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/16/21ca37f6ead61620c1672bfd0bdec0d3/d36ae24313c8ae3fdc0fa4d64a398a91/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Substituting these values, we will get:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Fair value of loan}&=\\dfrac{\\$2,577.21 \\times \\left(1-\\left(1+\\dfrac{0.05}{12}\\right)^{-300}\\right)}{0.05/12}\\\\\n&=\\dfrac{\\$2,577.21 \\times (1-0.284)}{0.0042}\\\\\n&=\\$439,352.94\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nThe amount that Ian will be willing to pay for the mortgage is the Fair value of the loan which is $\\$439,352.94$\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":403,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/16/21ca37f6ead61620c1672bfd0bdec0d3/52c699bd4f6f9d1a6349c643500d90aa/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":203,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/16/21ca37f6ead61620c1672bfd0bdec0d3/52c699bd4f6f9d1a6349c643500d90aa/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"**b.** \nInterest rates and bond prices move in opposite directions. This means that a decrease in the interest rate will increase the bond prices.\n\nHaving a long position in bonds will increase in value. This also means that the value of the mortgage loan will increase, thus, offsetting the incurred losses from the bond contracts. \n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":176,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/16/21ca37f6ead61620c1672bfd0bdec0d3/f837f837d60fcf743b9c70368ef1c86c/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":89,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/16/21ca37f6ead61620c1672bfd0bdec0d3/f837f837d60fcf743b9c70368ef1c86c/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"e1da1084-73d5-4362-9985-45a95f592e81","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881848,"exerciseName":"6","page":789,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"14f1fd0e-3510-450a-ab85-b873c5305225","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/